   "id": "3bd48f14-a890-497e-a1f8-bf281951b337",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating Collections - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "2fa2bb8f-fda9-4adc-8b3c-90f3ee62ff97",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating Sequences\n",
    "\n",
    "We saw in last section\n",
    "-> __getitem__\n",
    "-> assuming indexing started at 0\n",
    "-> iteration: __getitem__(0), __getitem__(1), etc..\n",
    "\n",
    "But iteration can be more general than based on sequential indexing\n",
    "All we need is:\n",
    "a bucket of items -> collection, container\n",
    "get next item -> no concept of ordering needed; just a way to get items out of container one by one (specific order not required - but can be)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "24bd5a50-9cb2-44ff-943a-54cef99c205d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example: Sets\n",
    "\n",
    "Sets are unordered collection of items\n",
    "\n",
    "s = {'x', 'y', 'b', 'c', 'a'}\n",
    "\n",
    "Sets are not indexable\n",
    "\n",
    "s[0] -> TypeError - set does not support indexing\n",
    "\n",
    "But sets are iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in s\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "y\n",
    "c\n",
    "x\n",
    "b\n",
    "a\n",
    "\n",
    "Note we haev no idea of order which elements are returned"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9aa90fcb-42fd-4cac-b838-6f29e0356de4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The concept of next\n",
    "\n",
    "For general iteration, all we need is get next item in collection\n",
    "If a collection object implements a get_next_item method\n",
    "we can get elements out of collection, on e by one:\n",
    "\n",
    "get_next_item()\n",
    "get_next_item()\n",
    "\n",
    "and we could iterate over collection\n",
    "\n",
    "for _ in range(10):\n",
    "    item = coll.get_next_item()\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "But how we know when to stop asking for next item?\n",
    "i.e. when all elements in collection have been returned by get_next_item()> -> StopIteration (built-in exception)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "edc005ce-6706-4554-9896-56df6012212e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Attempting to build Iterable Ourselves\n",
    "\n",
    "Try building class which will be collection of squares of integers\n",
    "We could make this sequence but want to avoid concept of indexing\n",
    "\n",
    "In order to implement a next method, we need to know what we have already handed out\n",
    "so we can hand out next item without repeating ourselves\n",
    "\n",
    "class Squares:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self.i = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def next_(self):\n",
    "        result = self.i ** 2\n",
    "        self.i += 1\n",
    "        return result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0bdf141e-56de-4439-a304-4ca34fe03318",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating over Squares\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = Squares()\n",
    "\n",
    "for _ in range(5):\n",
    "    item = sq.next_()\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "0\n",
    "1\n",
    "4\n",
    "9\n",
    "16\n",
    "\n",
    "There are a few issues\n",
    "-> collection is essentially infinite\n",
    "-> cannot use a for loop, comprehension, etc.\n",
    "-> we cannot restart iteration from beginning"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "154dfa2e-2f1a-4dad-9eeb-e6ad83a1ef81",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Refining the Squares Class\n",
    "\n",
    "We first tackle the idea of making the collection finite\n",
    "- we specify the size of the collection when we create the instance\n",
    "- we raise a StopIteration exception if next_ has been called too many times\n",
    "\n",
    "class Squares:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, length):\n",
    "        self.i = 0\n",
    "        self.length = length\n",
    "\n",
    "    def next_(self):\n",
    "        if self.i >= self.length:\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            result = self.i ** 2\n",
    "            self.i += 1\n",
    "            return result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "3cb334c3-0601-4325-872f-9a914a59f0fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating over Squares instances\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = Squares(5)\n",
    "\n",
    "while True:\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        item = sq.next_()\n",
    "        print(item)\n",
    "    except StopIteration:\n",
    "        break\n",
    "\n",
    "0\n",
    "1\n",
    "2\n",
    "4\n",
    "9\n",
    "16"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "7691cc50-be5c-44a1-b8c0-3b8b9a3f9a99",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Python's next() function\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember Python's len() function?\n",
    "We could implement that function for our custom type by implementing special method __len__\n",
    "\n",
    "Python has a built-in function: next()\n",
    "We could implement that function for our custom type by implementing special method __next__\n",
    "\n",
    "class Squares:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, length):\n",
    "        self.i = 0\n",
    "        self.length = length\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__(self):\n",
    "        if self.i >= self.length:\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            result = self.i ** 2\n",
    "            self.i += 1\n",
    "            return result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "583d81d2-f957-451a-a1f5-ff598aa08134",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating over Squares instances\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = Squares(5)\n",
    "\n",
    "while True:\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        item = next(sq)\n",
    "        print(item)\n",
    "    except StopIteration:\n",
    "        break\n",
    "\n",
    "0\n",
    "1\n",
    "2\n",
    "4\n",
    "9\n",
    "16\n",
    "\n",
    "We still have issues:\n",
    "- canmot iterate using for loops, comprehensions, etc.\n",
    "- once iteration starts we have no way of re-starting it\n",
    "- once all items have been iterated (using next) object becomes useless for iteration -> exhausted"
   ]
  },
